{\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 1  Introduction - What is a Qubit\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 A qubit is the name given to the quantum mechanical unit of information, analogous to the bit used in regular information technology
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_gentleintro \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{gentleintro}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The regular bit is simply the name given to the position of a logic gate, when used in the context of computing, and is represented in the computer as either a 0, the gate being \ldblquote closed\rdblquote , or a 1, meaning the gate is \ldblquote open\rdblquote . The name comes from a contraction of the words binary digit and so qubit is a {\i quantum binary digit}. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 Referring to the bit as corresponding to the state of a logic gate comes from the earliest computers, before the advent of the transistor, when they used mechanical valves to perform computations. Though this analogy falls down with modern computers where there are many different two state systems, it is useful in understanding the key concept which underlies modern computing - that a bit has exactly two possible states that it can exist in. These states can be described by many examples, on/off, up/down, positive/negative, in/out, etc{\f5\u775.}, but it is important to remember that it must be one or the other.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 By contrast, the qubit, because of its quantum mechanical nature, has the two states described by the bit, but also has the possibility of existing in a superposition of these states. This superposition of the two classical states can be to any degree, meaning that there are effectively an unlimited number of states available ranging from completely 0 to completely 1 with every combination of them in between. \par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 2  Qubits - A History\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Max Plank started the first work on quantum mechanics in the early 1900\rquote s when he described the quantum nature of radiation and then Erwin Schr\'f6dinger moved this work into a mathematical basis with his formulation of his famous, posthumously named, Schr\'f6dinger equation. The work of Alan Turing in 1946
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_turing \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{turing}}}
] led to the development of potential computational systems though it was not until the late 1950\rquote s that anything resembling the structure of today\rquote s computers was designed. From this point to now however, though the speeds and memory models have moved on, there is little difference in the way that classical computers operate.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The basic units inside a computer are the semiconductors and, as these continue to shrink in size, the laws that are used to describe them and predict they\rquote re behaviour will have to change. Whereas classical laws are sufficient to describe the electronic properties when the components are macroscopic in size, as the size decreases, quantum effects become more and more important and so the system must be treated as quantum not classical.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 A major breakthrough in quantum computing came in the early 1970\rquote s and early 80\rquote s when it was shown that a reversible Turing machine was theoretically possible (Charles Bennett, IBM, Yorktown Heights) and then formulatable using quantum mechanics (Paul Benioff, Argone National Laboratory).\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The first work into how the equivalent quantum mechanical gates might be created was carried out in the 1990\rquote s when the problems of de-coherence was also first met experimentally. When possible methods to overcome the limitations through error correction techniques were explored (Peter Shor, Bell Labs), the actual computer based on quantum effects was realised. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 Much of the current work in this area is concerned with the development of algorithms that would take advantage of the possibilities governed by quantum mechanics. The easiest method, and the only available method in classical computing, is to encode a single bit into each qubit used. But the qubit offers the possibility to use entanglement so that neither qubit carries a well defined amount of information but instead the information is contained in their duel state.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 This method of data transfer/storage means that other possible effects can be taken advantage of, including quantum teleportation and quantum error correction. These effects mean that the benefits of quantum computing are far greater than just increasing the density of gates on a chip or increasing the speed of calculations, but being able to perform calculations that would simply not be possible to program into a classical computer.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 3  Qubits - A Basic Understanding\par
\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb180 \fi0 {\*\bkmkstart BMeq_arbitarystate}3.1{\*\bkmkend BMeq_arbitarystate}  Mathematical Representation\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 The standard representation used in quantum information is using Dirac Braket notation and so we shall use this notation too. Using this notation, the superposition of a qubit in an arbitrary state is given by {\par
\pard\plain\s14\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqr\tx3105\tql\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
|{\u936*}{\f5\u9002*}\tab
={\u945*}|0{\f5\u9002*}+{\u946*}|1{\f5\u9002*},\tab
\tab{\b0 ()}\par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 where the coefficients {{\u945*}} and {{\u946*}} are the amplitudes of the qubit in the 0 and 1 \ldblquote directions\rdblquote  and {{\u936*}} is the resulting state.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 As in all of quantum mechanics, this final state represents the full range of possible states, but gives no information at to what state the object would be in if it were measured, it provides only probabilities. The probability of any one state is given by the absolute amplitude of the coefficient for that state, so that from equation {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMeq_arbitarystate \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{?}}}, the probability of measuring the qubit in the 0 state is {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ |{\u945*}|\\s\\up5({\fs18 2})}}{\fldrslt }}
} and the corresponding probability of it being in the 1 state is {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ |{\u946*}|\\s\\up5({\fs18 2})}}{\fldrslt }}
}. Since there are only two absolute states that exist and can be measured, there are constraints on the values that these coefficients can take. It follows that {\par
\pard\plain\s14\ql\sb120\sa120\keep\widctlpar\f0\tqr\tx3105\tql\tx3450\tqr\tx6900\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 \tab
