}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi0 simply because there must be a definite chance of measuring one or the other.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 In order to represent the different states of the qubit, a Bloch Sphere is used, where the possible states are represented in 3-dimensional space on a unit sphere
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_gentleintro \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{gentleintro}}}
], figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMfig_bloch \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{?}}}. A qubit can be in a superposition such that it can exit at any point on the surface of the sphere. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The possibilities for the location of a state of a qubit is limited to two degrees of freedom, located to the surface of the sphere. The freedom comes from the complex nature of the coefficients {{\u945*}} and {{\u946*}} and is limited from four by the constraint in equation {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMeq_constraint \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{?}}} and the fact that one of the coefficients can arbitrarily be set to be real since the overall state has no physical observable. \par
\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 3.2  Physical Representation\par
