\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 4  Qubits - Plausibility\par
\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb180 \fi0 4.1  Disadvantages\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Though it is proving to be one of the most successful theories of all time, in terms of experimental prediction and verification, quantum mechanics is also relatively young. This is not a bad thing, since it has many more applications to be applied to and has the potential to continue reshaping the theories we have for the universe. But it does mean that, in the even younger field of quantum computing, there are several key issues that would hold the quantum computer back from becoming a widespread application of this powerful area of science.\par
\pard\plain\s5\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 4.1.1  De-coherence\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 One of the most important problems with quantum computing, and specifically with the manufacture and use of a physical qubit is the issue of de-coherence. This is the loss of the quantum properties that the quantum computer would rely on, so that the components of the qubit return back to a purely classical state. Or, in other words, a loss of information from the system into the surroundings. It occurs when two objects, photons, electrons, etc{\f5\u775.}, that are entangled in a quantum system are disturbed and loose their entangled state. De-coherence is a major problem for the application of qubits to the quantum computer since the computer would have to rely on being able to store and then retrieve information in order to perform calculations and so would require the quantum system to remain coherent. The environment that surrounds the system is out of control and so any information that is passed there is lost.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The issue facing scientists is that it can be initialised by any smallest interaction with the surrounding environment or system. This means that, currently, the only way to avoid de-coherence is to try to keep the entire quantum system completely isolated. Because of the delicacy of the quantum state, the sort of interaction that can produce de-coherence is very small, such as slight temperature changes, or the collision of single atoms or molecules. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 Generally a quantum state will remain coherent, and so useful for applications in quantum computing, for a tiny length of time. De-coherence was first discussed in 1991
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_zurek_36 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{zurek\\s\\do5({\fs18 3})6}}}
], but still the best efforts have only extended the time before loss of information to 180{\charscalex50\~}seconds
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Steger08062012 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{Steger08062012}}}
]. Though this is a huge move forward from the milliseconds achievable only a few years ago, even this is quite an exaggeration since it relates to simply ensuring the qubit exhibits the necessary properties. As well as this, it also requires the system, and so equipment required, to operate at fantastically low temperatures with the aim of removing as much as possible of the external interference. The current record for actually storing any information and retrieving it again from such a system at roughly room temperature is far shorter, of the order of 1{\charscalex50\~}second
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_Maurer08062012 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{Maurer08062012}}}
].\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 One of the driving motivations for finding new ways of realising the qubit through different mechanisms is that the de-coherence times vary depending on the type of qubit used. For example, consider the photon qubit. This involves trapping an infra-red photon in an optical fibre. This has one of the shortest maximum coherence times, around 0.1{\charscalex50\~}ms. This is due to the extreme requirements of the system in order to preserve the quantum state, the optical fibre must be of extremely high quality and the photon must have exactly the frequency for which the fibre is the most transparent. This adds up to a huge challenge to extend the lifetime of these qubits.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 On the other hand, the {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {}\\s\\up5({\fs18 29}){{\i S}{\i i}}}}{\fldrslt }}
} nuclear spin in {{\field{\*\fldinst{ EQ {}\\s\\up5({\fs18 28}){{\i S}{\i i}}}}{\fldrslt }}
} has a much higher lifetime, at least 25{\charscalex50\~}seconds. Again this is due to the way these qubits are structured, this time being much more resilient to external interference.\par
\pard\plain\s5\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 4.1.2  Error Correction\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 In the classical computer, there are errors introduced to the calculations simply by the flow of electrons through wires and components is not perfect and so information can be distorted or lost. This can happen as the information about a piece of data is moved from one component to another, or within a single component. The data is transferred as single bits and so the change of a bit, from \ldblquote 1\rdblquote  to \ldblquote 0\rdblquote  or visa versa, is known as bit-flipping. The build up of these errors and successive bit-flips leads to noise that can distort an image or sound or cause a calculation to be incorrect. To counter this effect, which could be very serious if the computer is controlling important information or equipment, error correction is introduced.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The simplest type of classical error correction is called using redundancy. This involves increasing the number of times each bit is sent, so that, if one of those copies is damaged, there are still intact versions that can be relied on. For example, consider a piece of information being used inside a computer, for example the binary code, {\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \li512\ri512\fi330 001011101 \par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 If this information was sent again with redundancy, this might now look like, {\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \li512\ri512\fi330 000{\charscalex50\~}000{\charscalex50\~}111{\charscalex50\~}000{\charscalex50\~}111{\charscalex50\~}111{\charscalex50\~}111{\charscalex50\~}000{\charscalex50\~}111 \par
}\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 Now, if the first packet of 3 bits, representing the single bit, \lquote 0\rquote , is changed en route, so that now it contains \lquote 010\rquote , the receiver can compare the three bits in the group and use the bit that represents the majority of the three. In other words, there are till two remaining \lquote 0\rquote  bits and only one distorted 1 bit, so the \lquote 0\rquote  will be used, overcoming the error in transmission.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 This method is very effective for the classical example, but when applied to a quantum computer, is not transferable. One reason for this is that, in order to determine which was the correct unaltered state, each of the three qubits would have to be measured and then compared. But the quantum nature of the states would mean that the simple act of measuring would destroy their states and so not give an accurate representation. Secondly, the fact that the qubits can be in a superposition of different states means that there is a far greater, in fact infinite, number of different possible values that could be measured, and so a much greater scope for error. This would mean that a much higher number of qubits would have to be transferred in order to have enough states to compare with and know that the majority had not been subject to error. \par
\pard\plain\s4\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 4.2  Qubits - Advantages\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 We have discussed a few of the major disadvantages, though as time goes on, these are becoming fewer and fewer. As our understanding of the quantum behaviour of systems increases, so does our ability to manipulate it. Though most would agree that there is a long way to go, and that it is going to take some huge developments in technology and what it can provide to allow quantum computing to get to the point that classical computing has reached, there is potential.\par
\pard\plain\s5\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs24\sl240\slmult1 \sb120 \fi0 4.2.1  Error Correction\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 We saw previously how error correction can be easily implemented in a classical system using redundancy, but the quantum qubit means that this form of detection for the occurrence of errors is not possible. Despite this, there are still ways of overcoming the errors that are inevitably introduced to a system when it is exposed to the natural environment. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 Before we can understand how error correction can be applied to the quantum bit, we first need to know how the quantum equivalent of some of the logic gates used in classical computing work. Logic gates are the neurons to the brain that is the computer\rquote s CPU. They are gates that sometimes allow information to pass through them in certain configurations, and in others change the information if it has the right characteristics. Two simple examples are the AND and the NOT gate. The AND gate receives two streams of data and does a simple binary addition, whereas the NOT takes a single input and inverts it so that the opposite is produced. The tables that describe these gates are shown below as they as the basis of the quantum computer as well as the classical. {\par
