\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The receiver then makes measurements randomly of the qubits that have been sent using two analysers that detect if the qubit is polarised in the vertical/horizontal direction, or the diagonal direction. The sender does not reveal which direction setting was used to encode the \ldblquote 0\rdblquote s and \ldblquote 1\rdblquote s, meaning that the receiver and so also any evesdropper does not know either. When the receiver measures the information, quantum uncertainty means that half of the time the right answer is found. This is due to the baseis not being orthogonal to each other ands so a quantum measurement cannot determine between them. After the measurement, the photon is left in the state that it was measured to be in so an evesdropper would affect the data being sent. \par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 The receiver does not know how the data was encoded so can at most only select at random which basis set to asign each qubit measured. After the information has been received, the sender releases the settings for the analyser so that the receiver knows which basis set was used for each individual qubit. The receiver can then correctly pick out the key from the results. On average, the correct value will have been found half of the time and the measurements where the correct answer is not found are discarded. The remaining bits constitute the shared key that the two parties can use, knowing that no-one else can have intercepted the transmission of the key.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 One of the first experimental demonstrations of quantum cryptography was carried out in 2000 by a group at the University of Vienna using pairs of entangled photons
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_PhysRevLett_84_4729 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{PhysRevLett\\s\\do5({\fs18 8})4\\s\\do5({\fs18 4})729}}}
]. They transmitted the encoded qubits over a distance of 360{\charscalex50\~}m via an optical fibre showing that the principle is deffinitely possible. However, the errors in transmission and measurement meant that they were unable to extend the distance the data was transfered. In 2004 though, another group from Toshiba Research at Cambridge managed to securely encode, transfere and decode a still image over a distance of 122{\charscalex50\~}km via a standard telecom cable
[{\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BIB_gobby_3762 \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{gobby\\s\\do5({\fs18 3})762}}}
]. Figure {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMfig_quantumimage \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{?}}} shows the images that was transfered as well as the two keys that were generated and the decoded image. The small remaining errors in the image can be seen as defects to the colour, but overall, the image is very clearly the same as was transmitted.\par
\pard\plain\s3\ql\sb240\sa120\keepn\f0\b\fs32\sl240\slmult1 \sb240 \fi0 5  Qubits - Conclusion\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \sb60 \fi0 We have seen how the many advancements in quamtun theory have changed the way that we think about the world on a small scale. This is being applied more and more to the macroscopic scale, allowing us to take advantage of some truly extraordinary discoveries. There are also some very serious hurdles that need to be tackled. We have discussed a few here, but there are many that prevent quantum computing being used widely. As each new advancement is made, as is always the way, there are always a number of new challenges that require work to overcome.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 But the advances are starting to find uses, and are being implemented into the real world for industrial and commercial applications. In 2010 the FIFA World cup in South Africa used a version of the quantum crtypography discussed in section {\field{\*\fldinst{\lang1024 REF BMsec_safe_transfer \\* MERGEFORMAT }}{\fldrslt{?}}} to secure the transmission of videos, e-mails, and phone calls that were regularly relayed between the stadium and the nearby centers for police, firefighters, and military personnel. This demonstrated a trust in the very new technology that is needed for the expansion out of the research environment into general usage.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 Trust is an issue that several new areas of physics lack in the public eye, that prevents them, in many people\rquote s view, from becoming more mainstream. The reputation of nuclear power, for example, once it was propely understood what was going on, was seriously damaged by the disasters at Chernobyl and more recently Fukushima Daiichi. It is a reputation like this that would prevent quantum theory in the feild of computing and telecomunications from becoming the industry standard.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 It is to quanutm theory\rquote s advantage, therefore, that the word \ldblquote quantum\rdblquote  is quickly becoming a media \lquote buzz-word\rquote  because of the visually and theoretically impressive advancements that scientists are able to offer in this area. People are keen to show their interest in this feild and compnies are able to take advantage of this by directing money and effotr into research programs to feed a desire for this new and exciting technology.\par
\pard\plain\s0\qj\widctlpar\f0\fs22\sl240\slmult1 \fi340 If quantum thoery and it\rquote s associated sciences are able to keep up this interest and the level and significance of the funding and potential that it is currently showing, then the recent trends indicate that the quantum binary digit will play an even more significant role in daily life, perhaps, one day, surpassing the plain old classical bit.\par
